<TEXT>
space shuttle columbia could be 
launched on a secret military mission in about two weeks if nasa 
officials turn up no problems during todays flight readiness 
review 
one possible hitch could be a valve problem the cause of which 
engineers have been seeking for two days if the valve must be 
replaced it could add two to three days to the launch processing 
time 
the space agency said last week it hopes to launch columbia 
during the week of aug 7 with five astronauts and a defense 
department payload believed to be an advanced reconnaissance 
satellite 
a firm launch date announcement was expected late this afternoon 
after the valve problem has been thoroughly assessed and the 
readiness of the orbiter the payload the global tracking network 
and all other mission elements have been evaluated 
the decision will come at the conclusion of a twoday review 
headed by bill lenoir national aeronautics and space 
administrations acting associate administrator for space flight 
the valve problem was detected early monday following a brief 
test firing of columbias three auxiliary power units which 
provide hydraulic power for moveable control surfaces such as wing 
flaps rudder and speed brake 
radio data indicated a hydrazine fuel valve serving one of the 
units was stuck open when it should have been closed 
initial analysis indicated the valve worked properly and that a 
bad sensor might have given a faulty reading engineers continued 
studying the situation to learn exactly what went wrong 
columbias crew members are air force col brewster shaw the 
commander navy cmdr richard richards navy cmdr david leestma 
air force lt col james adamson and air force maj mark brown 
</TEXT>
