<TEXT>
a state judge on tuesday upheld gov mario 
cuomos agreement with the long island lighting company to have the 
state buy the shoreham nuclear power plant for 1 and have it 
dismantled 
a group of long island residents taxpayers business groups and 
labor unions had challenged the deal on the grounds that cuomo had 
usurped the legislatures power 
last year cuomo and lilco officials had negotiated a similar 
shoreham closing deal only to see it fall apart because the 
legislature wouldnt give its required approval 
cuomo castigating the legislature for being afraid of potential 
political fallout reached a new agreement with lilco officials in 
february that he said did not require legislative input or approval 
lou lewis a poughkeepsie ny lawyer representing the long 
island opponents of the agreement said kahns ruling would be 
appealed 
i feel the judge made some serious errors of fact and law 
said lewis i find this decision very surprising 
lewis said he had no fear of shoreham quickly being torn down 
he noted that in addition to his lawsuit a group of pronuclear 
scientists represented by the conservative atlantic legal 
foundation also has a suit against the agreement pending in state 
court and he noted that the federal nuclear regulatory commission 
still must approve the transfer of the shoreham license from lilco 
to the state 
under the shoreham agreement already approved by lilco 
shareholders and several state agencies involved the completed 
55 billion plant on the eastern end of long island would be sold 
to the state for 1 and then the state would tear it down at 
lilcos expense 
in return lilco has won agreement from the state for a series 
of annual electric rate increases of about 5 percent that are 
expected to go on for a decade or more lilco customers already pay 
among the highest electric rates in the nation and the agreement to 
have even higher rates is what had some legislators upset about 
backing any such deal 
cuomo has maintained that it is cheaper to close shoreham than 
to allow it to operate hes also argued that its unsafe to 
operate the plant because the area surrounding it couldnt be 
safely evacuated if there was an emergency 
should the agreement be completed it would mark the first time 
in this nations history that a completed nuclear power plant has 
ever been dismantled before going on line the shoreham plant 
has never operated at anything above a 5 percent testing level 
</TEXT>
