a ku klux klan leader who agreed to 
attend a race relations course to settle a lawsuit over a clash 
with civil rights marchers says the classroom sessions wont change 
his attitude toward blacks 
i will sit through that course but i will leave with the same 
opinion i walk in there with roger handley said tuesday 
handley former grand dragon of the knights of the ku klux klan 
was one of 10 people named in a federal lawsuit stemming from a 
1979 clash between robed klansmen and black civil rights marchers 
in decatur 
under a settlement filed tuesday in us district court the 
defendants agreed to pay 11500 in damages to the marchers 
perform community service and refrain from harassing blacks or 
joining any klan or white supremacist group for up to five years 
the klansmen also agreed to take a race relations course taught 
by civil rights leaders the rev joseph lowery president of the 
southern christian leadership conference said he would help lead 
the two onehour sessions probably next year in birmingham 
handley told the birmingham postherald the settlement was 
