<TEXT>
burmas military rulers have released 
nearly 4000 convicted criminals under a recent government amnesty 
the state newspaper reported today 
under an amnesty announced july 20 death sentences were 
commuted to life imprisonment life sentences were reduced to 10 
years and other punishments were cut by twothirds the order said 
criminal cases still being heard are to be closed 
the amnesty applies only to those who committed offenses before 
sept 18 1988 the day the military moved to crush a nationwise 
prodemocracy uprising it does not apply to cases of high treason 
or breaches of martial law stipulations imposed since then 
martial law is aimed at preventing an upsurge of popular 
discontent against authoritarian rule similar to that seen last 
year gatherings of more than five people are forbidden and 
freedom of speech is greatly curtailed 
on july 18 the eve of a planned opposition rally the military 
tightened martial law and threatened death sentences for offenders 
in five days since the amnesty was announced the working 
peoples daily the englishlanguage edition of the only legal 
newspaper in burma said 3944 prisoners had been released 
a total of 155 people on death row at the time of the 
announcement had been given reprieves the paper said 
the amnesty was announced the same day the military put under 
house arrest the countrys two leading opposition figures aung san 
suu kyi and tin oo of the national league for democracy it accused 
them of attempting to destroy the military and create anarchy in 
the country 
