<TEXT>
the european community said wednesday 
that president bushs decision to extend us steel import quotas 
was unnecessary because the american industry has made an 
impressive comeback 
bush said he took the measure announced tuesday to try to 
press negotiations to end other countries unfair trade practices 
and give the us industry more time to modernize 
but the european community west europes 12nation trading 
bloc complained about the decision 
after an uninterrupted period of protection a renewal of 
these accords in the steel sector is not necessary considering the 
remarkable progress registered by american steel it said 
the industry has improved both financially and competitively in 
recent years and the world outlook for steel has brightened it 
said 
in a response to the criticism thomas niles the us 
ambassador to the european community said the us action was 
designed to give more time to come up with a trading system based 
on freer markets 
we should try to turn steel trade into a marketdriven 
operation rather than one that is driven largely by government 
subsidies and interventions by governments in the market he said 
he predicted european officials will take a closer look at the 
program and will see it as in their interest to join with us in 
this effort to move toward a marketbased system 
the community also complained that the quotas have limited 
european steelmakers more than other foreign producers in gaining 
access to the us market 
the european blocs share of the american steel market tumbled 
from 8 percent before the quotas to 56 percent afterward 
according to its figures 
the trading bloc exported 59 million metric tons of steel 
products to the united states in 1988 a metric ton is equivalent 
to 2205 pounds or 11 short tons 
the quotas were first imposed by the reagan administration in 
1984 they were due to expire sept 30 
they set annual limits on the amount of steel that could be 
brought into the united states from 29 countries including those 
of the european community japan south korea and brazil 
the quotas were imposed at a time when the us industry was 
suffering heavy losses steel manufacturers complained foreign 
producers had an unfair advantage because of government subsidies 
and import restrictions 
american steelmakers acknowledge the us import quotas have 
helped their giant industry become profitable again but they argue 
they still need time to modernize their operations without 
competition from subsidized foreign products 
in his announcement bush said he had asked us trade 
representative carla hills to negotiate a 30month extension of 
voluntary restraint agreements that limit the 29 countries to 184 
percent of the us market the european communitys share of the 
total quota is 27 percent 
bushs quota extension will allow the overall foreign market 
share to rise by 1 percentage point per year until quotas are 
phased out entirely hills said that yearly increase would be 
allocated to countries that exhibit the most willingness to stop 
subsidizing their domestic industry 
bush said the restrictions will end on march 31 1992 
</TEXT>
