<TEXT>
a leading black magazine says the former 
white rhodesian government secretly burned the bodies of black 
nationalist guerrillas in an incinerator that it likened to the 
ovens of nazi germany 
the august issue of the independent parade magazine said the 
incinerator is hidden in thickly wooded grounds at chikurubi 
maximumsecurity prison near harare where scores of guerrillas 
were executed 
it said the nowidle incinerator was used to dispose of bodies 
of an unspecified number of guerrillas executed during the 
sevenyear war that forced independence and brought the black 
majorityruled nation of zimbabwe into existence in april 1980 
former rhodesian prime minister ian smith the last white ruler 
of this exbritish colony denied there were covert executions and 
said his government burned only papers in incinerators 
the magazine which claims a readership of more than 1 million 
in this southern african nation of 9 million people said the 
incinerator was rhodesias equivalent to the ovens the nazis used 
in world war ii 
parade described the incinerator as the size of a small house 
with a 10yard chimney extending through the roof according to a 
stamp embossed into its heavy iron casing the incinerator was 
called macroburn by its makers in johannesburg the magazine 
said 
it must be one of the most efficient crematoriums in southern 
africa said political affairs minister eddison zvobgo who is 
campaigning for it to be declared a national memorial 
we think the incinerator should become a national monument 
like those in germany today he said 
the incinerator is equipped with fanassisted oilfired burners 
and at one end features a highwalled sluice yard where 
truckloads of corpses allegedly were dumped said zvobgo who was 
zimbabwes first justice minister 
he said that in 1980 president robert mugabes new government 
found no accurate records of guerrilla executions and believes most 
were destroyed by outgoing rhodesian authorities 
between 1976 and 1979 zvobgo said an unknown number of 
