the european parliament the only one of the eecs institutions 
to be democratically elected is frequently dismissed as no more 
than a debating chamber 
specifically addressing this point the 45year old spanish 
lawyer said the parliament should make its debates more serious 
and to the point always and in all circumstances 
he was alluding to the bodys propensity to adopt resolutions 
and reports on human rights abuses or natural catastrophes on the 
other side of the globe 
crespo said the parliaments prime concern must be the 
immediate problems which directly affect european citizens 
for the time being it can amend or reject the eecs budget 
which only becomes operational once the parliaments president has 
signed it 
it also can dismiss all 17 members of the eecs executive 
commission which drafts community laws and can prevent or delay 
legislation from going into force by sending drafts back to the 
commission 
the parliament must also be consulted on certain measures aimed 
at creating a single market by the end of 1992 
it can veto or delay some eec treaties with other countries and 
new applications for common market membership must gain at least 
260 votes in the parliament to be accepted 
however the parliament cannot initiate legislation and in 
economic and monetary affairs its opinion does not have to be taken 
into account a situation crespon criticized 
we are entitled to demand parliaments full participation in 
the work of the intergovernmental conference on economic and 
monetary union he said referring to a plan to create full 
monetary union among the 12 member states 
