<TEXT>
ponies werent the only ones to get wet 
at the 64th annual wild pony swim wednesday 
some people in a crowd of about 30000 waited more than five 
hours in rain mud and swarms of mosquitoes to get the best view of 
the ponies being herded across the channel from assateague island 
to chincoteague on virginias eastern shore 
lonnie poling of san antonio texas got to the marshy shore 
about 5 am 
just in time for the thunder and lightning and rain he said 
as he pressed against a fence 
the polings and others stood through the brief downpour and 
stayed put as the mosquitoes came out and temperatures headed into 
the 80s 
finally low tide arrived and at about 1015 am the ponies 
made the 10minute swim tourists applauded and snapped pictures of 
the animals heads bobbing above the water 
the ponies seemed oblivious to the excitement as they calmly 
walked ashore and munched on marsh grass before they were herded 
through the streets to the towns carnival grounds to be auctioned 
off 
members of the chincoteague volunteer fire department hope to 
sell 30 to 50 of the ponies thursday to thin the herd and raise 
money for the animals upkeep during the winter 
the roundup made famous in misty of chincoteague and other 
childrens books by marguerite henry began in 1925 to finance the 
volunteer fire department 
firefighters now use the money to support the herd of ponies on 
assateague located just off the atlantic ocean side of the 
peninsula that forms chesapeake bay 
no one is sure how the ponies got to assateague the most 
commonly accepted theory is that they are descendants of horses 
hidden on the island by early settlers who wanted to avoid paying 
taxes on the animals 
a more romantic story holds that the ponies escaped from a 
spanish galleon that was wrecked off the coast more than 300 years 
ago 
the auction usually raises 12000 to 18000 said everett 
lewis who was president of the fire department last year 
they never do pay for themselves it costs us more to keep 
them he said 
he said the firefighters will make up the difference with money 
raised at their twoweek carnival that ends saturday 
barbara andrews of rochester nh won a raffle for the first 
young pony that emerged from the channel wednesday but she asked 
that the animal be returned to its island home 
he belongs here she said momentarily forgetting she had 
won a female pony we dont want him to be separated 
tim huddleston of cookeville tenn said he came to show the 
ponies to his horseloving children tiffany 9 and chad 6 
they read the books and came in town and saw the movie and 
been over here since 5 oclock this morning he said 
