<TEXT>
a former beechnut nutrition corp president 
whose conviction for intentionally distributing phony apple juice 
for babies was dismissed will be tried again in federal court a 
judge said wednesday 
the executive 55yearold niels l hoyvald was convicted in 
february 1988 in us district court in brooklyn on some 350 counts 
of willfully violating the federal food drug and cosmetic act 
he was accused of marketing as pure apple juice what was really 
sugar water containing little if any apple 
in march a threejudge panel in the 2nd us circuit of appeals 
threw out the conviction ruling that technically those violations 
were tried in the wrong jurisdiction 
the judges in a 21 decision said the prosecution failed to 
prove the case should have been heard in the district where the 
trial was held 
on wednesday us district judge thomas j platt ruled that a 
retrial on the charges that were overturned would open aug 21 
during the original trial the jury was unable to reach a 
verdict on a conspiracy charge and 18 counts of mail fraud against 
hoyvald and prosecutors said they would retry him on those charges 
in brooklyn 
the government is determined to see this case through to the 
finish said thomas h roche the lead government prosecutor 
the conduct that he engaged in is not something you just wink at 
and say goodbye 
a second beechnut official john f lavery 57 a former vice 
president for manufacturing at the beechnut plant in canajoharie 
ny was convicted with hoyvald of knowingly marketing the phony 
juice 
the appeals court also reversed some 400 counts against lavery 
but allowed conspiracy and mailfraud convictions to stand lavery 
said he would take his case to the us supreme court both men 
sentenced to a year and a day in jail are free pending appeal 
beechnut pleaded guilty in 1987 to 215 counts of shipping 
mislabeled products and paid a 2 million fine 
the fort washington pa company is the nations secondlargest 
babyfood maker after the gerber products co 
leonard borrino a beechnut spokesman said nestle stopped 
paying hoyvalds legal expenses in october and fired him in 
december 
in a similar case three men were charged tuesday in chicago 
with conspiracy for selling millions of cases of orange juice that 
allegedly were diluted with beet sugar waste water and other 
products the federal charges accuse two former owners and a top 
executive of the nowdefunct bodines inc of mislabeling juice sold 
from 1978 to 1985 
