<DOCNO> AP890726-0176 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
two heart drugs that were dropped from a 
federal study earlier this year are still important in the 
treatment of patients with lifethreatening irregular heartbeats a 
food and drug administration expert said wednesday 
dr robert temple director of one of two fda offices of drug 
evaluation said that although the drugs encainide and flecainide 
are no longer recommended for use with patients with mild heartbeat 
problems the drugs give doctors another way to possibly control 
very serious cardiac irregularities 
the drugs are useful for those people who are in a fairly 
desperate situation he said in an interview there are a lot 
of drugs to treat heart disease and none of them work all the 
time you need a full complement of drugs in that situation 
encainide is marketed by bristolmyers under the brand name 
enkaid and flecainide is sold by 3m riker under the name tambocor 
the two drugs were used in a national institutes of 
healthdirected study called the cardiac arrhythmia suppression 
trials or cast 
in this study encainide and flecainide were given to patients 
who had suffered heart attacks and then experienced mild or 
asymptomatic extra heartbeats 
the drugs were dropped from the trials last april after the nih 
found that more of the cast patients taking the medication were 
dying suddenly than were patients in the study who were taking only 
sugar pills 
a board monitoring cast found that among 730 patients receiving 
encainide or flecainide there were 57 cardiac arrests while among 
725 patients in the study taking only placebos 22 died of cardiac 
arrest 
the study was designed to see if reducing those extra beats 
that are known to be associated with excess risk would improve 
survival said temple obviously it didnt 
cast continues however using a third drug moricizine which 
was not associated with increased numbers of premature deaths this 
drug is not now on the market 
temple said the medical logic of cast combatting the disease 
by controlling the symptoms has been applied successfully in many 
medical studies for instance he said it been shown that 
controlling high blood pressure can reduce the risk of heart attack 
the fda doctor said encainide and flecainide remain in wide use 
because they work well with some patients he said no patient 
taking the drugs should change medication without physician 
approval 
a philadelphia physician dr joel morganroth of graduate 
hospital said that a survey he took of cardiologists before cast 
was modified showed that about half of the 250 doctors who 
responded were prescribing the drugs to control heartbeat 
irregularities in patients like those in the nih study 
he said in an interview that based on data from this survey and 
from other statistical studies there may have been up to 3000 
persons who died prematurely while taking these drugs 
for a brief period on tuesday the associated press reported 
erroneously that these deaths were connected to the cast studies 
morganroth said he surveyed only doctors who were not in the drug 
trials he said also that his estimate of the number who may have 
died while taking these drugs was only a rough number based on 
statistical assumptions 
</TEXT>
