<TEXT>
a mystery fungus perhaps from japan has 
riddled gypsy moths in the northeast this summer and may turn into 
a new weapon against the destructive pests the agriculture 
department said wednesday 
this is the first time a fungus has been known to cause a 
massive dieoff of gypsy moth caterpillars in north america said 
entomologist ann hajek of the departments agricultural research 
service i saw single trees with thousands of caterpillar 
corpses 
hajek who is based at the agencys laboratory in ithaca ny 
has been working to identify the fungus which was found in the 
western connecticut towns of wilton and hamden she said the same 
fungus probably killed the pests in areas of massachusetts new 
york new jersey pennsylvania and new hamphshire 
whatever the fungus is its definitely an addition to our 
arsenal of weapons against gypsy moths she said it could 
provide a new method for biological control for these pests 
hajek said its possible that the fungus is entomophaga 
maimaiga a fungus imported from its native japan for testing 
against gypsy moth caterpillars but she said no releases of the 
japanese fungus were made in the areas where the mystery fungus 
has been found 
