in loan guarantees to spur private research and development in such 
areas as advanced television 
we do have several concerns about particular provisions in 
this proposal including the loan guarantee plan murrin told the 
senate commerce science and transportation committee 
we have progressed to the point where we agree with the 
purposes behind these programs but there may be more 
costeffective alternatives by which we could achieve the same 
objectives murrin said we have to make choices about which 
programs would be most important and what level of support would 
provide us with a critical mass to ensure success 
murrin is a longtime executive at westinghouse who assumed his 
commerce post only a month ago he said commerce secretary robert 
mosbacher had asked him to head the departments role in addressing 
technology competitiveness issues such as highdefinition 
television 
he said he considered it crucial that the united states 
develop hdtv which would use semiconductors and other advanced 
technology to generate highquality images proponents say hdtv 
could revitalize a sagging us consumer electronics industry and 
have important military medical educational applications 
sen john mccain rariz suggested that if hdtv is so 
important maybe we need to put our money where our mouth is 
and that perhaps it needs presidential attention just not the 
secretary of commerce 
congress is considering ways to help a fledgling us hdtv 
industry overtake the big lead that japan and europe already have 
in this area congress asked mosbacher earlier this year to 
recommend quickly ways the government might build a us industrial 
policy on advanced electronics 
but murrin said it would be some weeks before a report was 
forthcoming because expert consultants could not agree on what time 
frame to establish for development complicated new technologies 
murrin noted that president bush has proposed that new 
technology be spurred by a reduction in the capital gains tax a 
permanent research and development tax credit and changes in 
antitrust laws to encourage joint rampd and production ventures 
the hollings bill the technology administration authorization 
act of 1989 would authorize fiscal 1990 appropriations for the 
technology administration which includes the national institute of 
standards and technology 
among other things the bill authorizes funds for nists 
inhouse laboratory programs its technology extension activities 
and loan guarantees to raise 50 million in seed money for 
industryled projects in areas such as advanced electronics and 
television superconductivity manufacturing and xray lithography 
a new method of making semiconductor chips 
the 305 million for the technology administration would be 
combined with 155 million already authorized in the 1988 omnibus 
trade act 
the bill would exclude foreign companies which murrin said may 
not be in americas best interests he said he favored considering 
foreign companies requests to join rampd consortia on a casebycase 
basis 
