<TEXT>
the european community today criticized 
president bushs decision to extend steel import quotas saying the 
american industry has made an impressive comeback in recent years 
bush said he took the measure in an effort to press negotiations 
to end other countries unfair trade practices and give the us 
industry more time to modernize its operations 
but the european community the 12nation trading bloc 
protested 
after an uninterrupted period of protection a renewal of 
these accords in the steel sector is not necessary considering the 
remarkable progress registered by american steel it said in a 
statement 
the industry has improved both financially and competitively 
and the world outlook for steel has brightened it said 
the community also complained the quotas have limited european 
steelmakers access to the american market but other foreign 
producers have not been restricted 
it said it wanted more information from the united states about 
bushs decision 
thomas niles the new american ambassador to the ec said we 
look forward to discussing this program with them 
in an interview he said the us action was designed to give 
more time to come up with a marketbased system for trading in 
steel 
we should try to turn steel trade into a marketdriven 
operation rather than one that is driven largely by government 
subsidies and interventions by governments in the market he said 
he suggested ec officials when they take a closer look at the 
program will see it as in their interest to join with us in this 
effort to move toward a marketbased system 
the communitys share of the american steel market tumbled from 
8 percent before the quotas to 56 percent afterward according to 
ec figures the trading bloc exported 59 million metric tons of 
steel products to the united states in 1988 
the quotas were first imposed by the reagan administration in 
1984 they were due to expire on sept 30 
they set annual limits on the amount of steel that could be 
brought into the united states from 29 countries including those 
of the european community japan south korea and brazil 
the quotas were imposed at a time the american industry was 
suffering heavy losses steel manufacturers complained foreign 
producers had an unfair advantage because of hefty government 
subsidies and import restrictions 
they now say the us import quotas have helped the giant 
industry become profitable again but they argue they still need 
time to bring their operations uptodate without competition from 
subsidized foreign products 
in his announcement tuesday bush said he had asked us trade 
representative carla hills to negotiate a 30month extension of the 
voluntary restraint agreements that limit the 29 countries to 184 
percent of the us market the european communitys share of the 
total quota is 27 percent 
bush said the restrictions will end on march 31 1992 
</TEXT>
