<TEXT>
assemblyline workers who once embraced 
japanesestyle team management voted wednesday on whether to make 
nissan the first wholly japaneseowned auto plant in the united 
states to be unionized 
antiunion workers predicted a decisive victory for nissan motor 
manufacturing usa the united auto workers seeking to organize 
2400 hourly employees also forecast success although more 
cautiously 
the vote represents a stern test of uaw muscle and a challenge 
to automakers strategy of locating plants in the antiunion south 
the union campaign at the 6yearold plant has also called into 
question japanese industrys reputation for enlightened management 
workers who once sang the praises of nissan management in which 
the shop is organized into teams whose members rotate tasks have 
charged that the plant is run at a breakneck speed that has 
resulted in a high rate of injury 
nissan has warned that a union could jeopardize benefits and 
plant unity and that the automaker will be a tough bargainer if the 
union wins 
balloting at the 760 million plant was expected to end early 
thursday an announcement of the outcome was expected before dawn 
the union needs a majority of the votes cast 
chris shelton a quality inspector who has been at the plant 
since it opened said he voted against the union and expected the 
uaw to lose badly 
if therere so many people happy with the plant why should 
they get any votes or at least as many as they need shelton 
said 
i think its going to go fairly heavily for the workers 
against the union said ken roden an antiunion employee just 
from talking to workers around the plant somewhere around 75 
percent 
maxey irwin a union spokesman said the uaw was confident of 
a victory but i am not predicting percentages 
the uaw represents workers at japanese plants jointly owned by 
the big three us automakers but has no foothold in the nations 
wholly japanese owned plants nissan toyota in georgetown ky 
and honda in marysville ohio 
the union tried to organize workers at marysville but backed out 
without an election in what a regional uaw official called a 
humiliating defeat 
the uaw represents workers at a flat rock mich plant owned by 
mazda motor manufacturing usa corp a wholly owned subsidiary of 
mazda motor corp of japan but ford motor co owns 25 percent of 
the parent company 
nissan has produced more than 1 million pickup trucks and sentra 
cars since the plant began operation in june 1983 about 15 miles 
south of nashville more than 3100 people work at the plant which 
plans to add a third model in 1992 
labor observers have characterized the vote as crucial for the 
uaw which has seen membership drop by 33 percent in the past 10 
years 
whether the union wins or not the votes important because 
the uaw remains one of the strongest if not the strongest labor 
unions in the united states because it has complete coverage of gm 
ford and chrysler and these new japanese transplants the 
unorganized ones represent a threat to that power base said 
harry katz a labor relations professor at cornell university 
katz said he does not understand why nissan so strongly opposes 
the union 
regardless of whether the union wins or loses theres going 
to be a lot of workers really mad he said and thats going to 
cost the company in lost productivity 
roden wearing a bright red tshirt that read vote no was 
one of three employees who spoke at a companysponsored news 
conference hours before the voting 
we can lose things if the uaw wins some of our fringe 
benefits such as our leasecar program the 401k benefits said 
roden those are the tangible things the intangible stuff is 
what im most concerned about the team concept that they have here 
between labor and management we work together 
the uaw has estimated that the pace of the production has 
injured 18 percent of the workers nissan claims its health and 
safety record is better than most us automakers 
the uaw forced the vote held under the auspices of the national 
labor relations board by getting signatures from 33 percent of the 
workers in a drive kicked off in january 1988 with an appearance by 
uaw president owen bieber 
