<TEXT>
the senate approved legislation on wednesday 
that would boost federal timber sales impose new restrictions on 
lobbyists and take a slap at federal financing of controversial art 
the measure provides 109 billion for various federal land 
indian energy natural resource and cultural programs for the 1990 
fiscal year which begins oct 1 under the interior department and 
related agencies final passage came on a voice vote 
with the house having passed an 111 billion version of the 
bill on july 12 the legislation was the first of the 13 annual 
appropriations bills financing the government to clear both 
chambers of congress this year the senate and house will have to 
hammer out identical texts before president bush can sign it into 
law 
the senate legislation contains bonuses for energy and timber 
interests and setbacks for environmentalists 
with a bow to the public concern about oil spills raised by a 
series of tanker accidents in recent months the bill accepts a 
moratorium that the house placed on the leasing of 84 million acres 
of federal offshore waters for oil and gas drilling a larger area 
by far than the redlined zones imposed by congress in previous 
years 
but it eliminates house language blocking the government from 
taking preliminary steps to lease several tracts off the coasts of 
california and the northeast 
the senate voted 7227 to strip a clause sponsored by sen 
james mcclure ridaho banning oil tankers from waters where 
leasing moratoria are in force the prohibition would increase 
pressure to ease leasing restrictions 
mcclure argued that tanker accidents are far more likely than 
spills from offshore drilling which he said doesnt have a 
safety problem it has a public relations problem 
but opponents complained that the provision would drive up the 
costs of petroleum products for residents of the large portions of 
the country whose offshore waters have drilling restrictions 
its designed to make them sorry they have championed 
moratoria and deferrals and not drilling off their banks said 
sen dale bumpers dark 
the senate also expressed opposition to house provisions 
requiring federal consideration of repurchasing leases of tracts 
off the alaskan coast in reaction to the recent prince william 
sound oil spill instead the senate directed the fish and wildlife 
service to study the effects of the spill on nearby fisheries 
the legislation would lift court restrictions obtained by 
environmental groups on the cutting of hundreds of thousands of 
acres of timber on federal lands in california oregon and 
washington if the environmentalists and the governments 
timberselling agencies cannot agree by oct 1 on terms that would 
make 125 billion board feet available the provision sponsored by 
sens mark hatfield of oregon ranking republican on the 
appropriations committee and brock adams dwash would protect 
some trees that are the habitat of the rare spotted owl 
the chairman of the appropriations panel sen robert byrd 
dwva included new constraints on lobbyists a reaction to the 
recent scandals involving the department of housing and urban 
development and other agencies 
recipients of federal grants contracts and loans would be 
barred from using government funds to pay lobbyists who helped them 
obtain the money all lobbyists who help people pursuing federal 
contracts would have to report their activities to the government 
including their earnings 
every senator in this body ought to be repulsed by the 
perception that we will dole out the bucks if stroked by the right 
consultant byrd said 
the bill would provide 1702 million to the national endowment 
for the arts which provides grants to artists and art 
organizations 
but it sliced 45000 from the endowments budget the amount it 
had spent this year on a pair of shows that several lawmakers have 
said they found offensive one was an exhibit of photographs by the 
late robert mapplethorpe depicting homosexual and sadomasochistic 
acts 
the measure would apportion 13 billion to the bureau of indian 
affairs 231 million more than bush sought 408 million for 
energy conservation programs for which bush wanted only 96 
million and 228 million to continue filling the strategic 
petroleum reserve the administration sought 35 million for the 
emergency reserve because it wanted to continue filling the storage 
caves on the gulf coast at a slower rate 
